message.content:
Here is how you can make a FastAPI app CORS compatible:

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI, CORSMiddleware

app = FastAPI()

origins = [
    "http://localhost.tiangolo.com",
    "https://localhost.tiangolo.com",
    "http://localhost",
    "http://localhost:8080",
]

app.add_middleware(
    CORSMiddleware,
    allow_origins=origins,
    allow_credentials=True,
    allow_methods=["*"],
    allow_headers=["*"],
)
```

This enables CORS for the specified origins. The allow_credentials=True allows sending cookies from the frontend. The allow_methods and allow_headers set to "*" allows all methods and headers.

You can also set more restrictive CORS settings by specifying only the required origins, methods, headers etc.

Some key points:

- The CORSMiddleware should be added before any routers.
- The allowed origins can be restricted to your frontend URLs only.
- Allow credentials only if needed.
- Restrict methods and headers to only required ones if possible.

So this sets up a basic permissive CORS config for a FastAPI app.

Here is how to enable CORS for all origins in FastAPI:

```python
from fastapi import FastAPI
from fastapi.middleware.cors import CORSMiddleware

app = FastAPI()

origins = ["*"]

app.add_middleware(
    CORSMiddleware,
    allow_origins=origins,
    allow_credentials=True,
    allow_methods=["*"],
    allow_headers=["*"],
)
```

The key points:

- Set origins to ["*"] to allow all origins
- Enable allow_credentials if you want to allow sending cookies
- Allow all methods and headers with ["*"]

This enables CORS access from any origin to the FastAPI app.

Do note that allowing all origins is not suitable for production applications. It's better to restrict origins to your specific frontend URLs for security.

But for development, allowing all origins is a quick way to enable CORS in FastAPI.
